    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Does alcohol affect muscle growth after 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes. Alcohol directly suppresses muscle protein synthesis — the process your body uses to repair and build muscle. Research shows even moderate drinking (3–5 drinks) can reduce MPS by 24–37% for up to 24 hours. After 40, when MPS is already less efficient, this effect is more significant than it was when you were younger.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How many drinks affects muscle protein synthesis?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Most research points to 3 or more drinks as the threshold where meaningful MPS suppression occurs. One to two drinks with a protein-rich meal appears to have a relatively minor effect. Timing matters as much as quantity — drinking immediately after a workout is significantly more damaging than drinking on a rest day.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Does alcohol cancel out protein intake?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Not entirely, but it reduces how effectively your body uses the protein you eat. Alcohol suppresses the signaling pathway your body uses to convert dietary protein into muscle tissue. You can still eat your protein target on a night you drink — it just won't be utilized as efficiently as it would be otherwise.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the best strategy for drinking and maintaining muscle after 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Three strategies help most: (1) Don't drink on the same day as a hard workout — that combination suppresses MPS exactly when demand is highest. (2) Eat protein before and during drinking, not just after. (3) Keep it to 1–2 drinks when you do drink near a training window. The goal isn't abstinence — it's knowing the cost and managing it.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is beer or wine worse for muscle protein synthesis?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The effect on MPS is driven by ethanol content, not the type of drink. A standard beer, a glass of wine, and a shot of spirits each contain roughly the same amount of ethanol and produce a similar suppressive effect. What differs is how quickly you reach the suppressive dose — liquor consumed quickly reaches the threshold faster.</div>
      </div>

